%%% Owen's Ye Olde Macro Definitions %%%
% The philosophy of this macro package is that LaTeX code has a disadvantage over handwriting
% because handwriting is more flexible. However, it also has an advantage in that it can be
% self-documenting. Therefore, we provide macros such as \integer, or \real, to use instead
% of \mathbb{Z} or \mathbb{R}. When two mathematical concepts use the same notation, this allows
% us to disambiguate it in the LaTeX.

% This helps us in writing papers because the source code becomes much more legible. Rather
% than a description of what something should look like on the page, it almost becomes like
% a pronunciation guide to what could be a dense tangle of notation.

% Furthermore, correct use of LaTeX is somewhat difficult. There are spacing subtleties that
% LaTeX can handle for you if you tell it which things are unary/binary operators, and use
% \colon instead of : when defining functions. These macros help with this; whenever possible
% a macro is declared using one of the \DeclareXXX family, which automatically gives it the
% correct spacing.

% Pared down for thermostatics paper

\ProvidesPackage{macros}

